Nissan Skyline GT-R (E-BNCR33) V-Spec ('97 spec)
The R33 Skyline was unveiled at 1993, but the GT-R variant was not available until two years later (1995). Despite grew slightly bigger, heavier & longer compared to the previous BNR32 GT-R, it (BNCR33) was surprisingly exceeding the BNR32 in every departments. Equiped with tweaked RB26DETT (280 PS & 375 Nm), ATTESA-ETS Pro & Super HICAS, this GT-R's balance had improved slightly. It was even set 21 seconds faster from previous BNR32 on N√ºrburgring Nordschleife's lap time & continued the 50 wins (from 50 starts) which had been set by BNR32 GT-R in Super Taikyu N1 class.
*It was the first GT-R that entered the Le Mans 24 Hours in GT1 class, which saw the road legal version of Nismo GT-R LM (based on JGTC GT500 car)
**The 4-door GT-R (still based on BNCR33) was buid by Autech

Nissan Skyline GTS-25t Type M (ECR33) Coup√© Spec II
In 1993, the new 9th Skyline (R33) was introduced. In this generation, all the Skylines lineup were powered solely by inline 6-cylinder engine. As the RB20DE was discontinued (leaving the single cam RB20E as a lower GTS trim), the higher GTS trims were all powered by RB25DE (GTS-25 & GTS-25t). For GTS-25t Type M, the RB25DET delivers 250PS & 294 N.m. During 1996, the Spec II was introduced, which saw the significant upgrade on engine & enhanced exterior.
*Some of the Skyline trims had equipped with Super HICAS, which used the electric actuator to steer the rear wheel (slightly advanced from the previous hydraulic HICAS).
**There was even a higher ECR33 trim called 280 Type MR P.Ride, which powered by RB28DETT (actually a stroked up & twin-turbocharged RB25DET) built by REINIK (another Nissan's motorsport arm). Only 7 units were built.

Nissan Skyline GT-R (E-BNR32) with Nismo Custom Parts
In 1989, when R32 Skyline made its debut, GT-R was evoked again after its 16 years of hiatus. Powered with RB26DETT bursting 276 hp (due to "Gentlemen's Agreement" that every powerful car should be rated at 276 hp) & 361 N.m of torque, combined with ATTESA E-TS & HICAS, making it the fastest (& far advanced) Japanese production car at that time. It didn't take a long time to conquer every Japanese Group A Race with 29 victories in total (1990-1993) & also took the victories in Macau Guia GP (1990), 24 Hours of Spa (1991), Bathurst 1000 (1991-1992) & Pikes Peak Hillclimb Open Class (1993).
The BNR32 Skyline GT-R were offered in standard trim (N1-spec also available), V-Spec & V-Spec II (both also offered in N1-spec), & Nismo version.

Nissan Skyline GTS-R (E-HR31/KHR31)
In 1985, the R31 Skyline (known as "Seventh Skyline" due to being 7th gen. Skyline) was released as four-door sedan & station wagon, in which later, the two-door coup√© version was available in 1986, named GTS. This Skyline generation also saw the rise of electronic-controlled 4-wheel steering system (HICAS / High Capacity Actively-Controlled Suspension) & comeback of DOHC inline-6 engine since last used in KPGC110 GT-R in 1973. In order to take the Group A's title, Nissan alongside Nismo (Nissan's motorsport & tuning arm) built the GTS-R to fulfil those regulation. This is the special version that ended up getting its own specialized RB20DET-R which pumped up 210 PS of power & 245 N.m of torque. Due to being a Group A homologation model, only 800 units of GTS-R were built
*This is the last Skyline designed by mastermind Shinichiro Sakurai which later continued by Naganori Ito

Nissan Skyline "JAPAN" (KHGC210/211), the least desirable, yet the most patriotic Skyline ever produced. As the Skyline went back to basic, this left the 2000GT-E as a higher trim. In order to diverse the trims, Nissan was decided to put the turbocharged one (with L20ET) as a top variant (2000GT-EX) & NA one (with L20E) as a lower-to-middle variant (2000GT-ES). This was the first Skyline equipped with turbocharged engine. Despite for not having the blow-off valve & intercooler, this was the "One-Step-Ahead" engineering advance at that time
*This was the third Skyline exported to European market after "Hakosuka" GLC10 2000GT & 2400GT & HGLC110 Datsun 240K GT
